{"title":"Cthulhu Worldbuilding: When Your Mythos Needs a PR Firm","body":"Look, I've covered enough product launches to know when I'm looking at a pitch deck. The Lovecraftian mythos works best when it stops selling the monster and lets the world feel indicted by its presence.

Cthulhu is not scary because he is big. He is scary because the setting keeps implying that human certainty is a flimsy legal defense against a universe that never signed the contract.

The best creature design in this lane should feel like evidence from a case nobody wants reopened: anatomy that almost makes sense, scale cues that make witnesses feel small, and one impossible detail that refuses to become a clean explanation.","tags":["#cthulhu","#lovecraft","#worldbuilding","#creaturedesign","#horror"],"need_image":false,"image_prompt":null,"image_alt":null}
